<H4>    Russia Opposes Air Strikes </H4>

<F P=102> OW2204212794 Beijing XINHUA in English 2002 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 22 (XINHUA) -- Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev said on Friday [22 April] that Russia is 
against the expansion of air strikes on Bosnian Serbs currently 
discussed by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO). 
  After his talks with visiting Danish Foreign Minister Niels 
Helveg Petersen, Kozyrev reminded reporters of "strongly 
negative estimation" of Bosnian Serb attacks on civilian 
facilities and, especially, a hospital in the Moslem-held town 
of Gorazde, noting that the international community has the 
right to work for termination of criminal actions. 
  At the same time, the Russian minister pointed out, a 
military response of NATO "would not be the best choice." 
  "Russia, the United States, the United Nations and the 
European Union should draw up a common approach to the Bosnian 
problem," Kozyrev said, describing this as "very important." 

</TEXT>

