<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Clinton Warns Serbs on Air Strikes </H4>

<F P=102> OW2204212894 Beijing XINHUA in English 2009 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204212894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 22 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton warned the Bosnian Serbs today that they "should not 
doubt NATO's willingness to act" on wider air strikes in the 
former Yugoslav Republic. 
  In a joint press conference with visiting Greek Prime 
Minister Andreas Papandreou shortly after NATO's fresh ultimatum 
for the Serbs, Clinton said Serb acts in Gorazde "justify firm 
action." 
  Papandreou, meanwhile, expressed Greek concerns and 
reservation for the NATO decision for fear of wider violence, 
although it did not vote against it. 
  "It's a fire that can spread very fast," Papandreou said. 
"On the Balkan peninsula, we have really dynamite on our hands," 
  Under the NATO ultimatum, the Bosnian Serbs should stop 
their 
assault immediately and pull out their heavy weapons before 
12:01 A.M. Sunday (local time) from a two miles radius from the 
center of Gorazde, one of six U.N.-designated "safe areas," or 
risk NATO air strikes. 
  The NATO decision also demands that the Serbs allow U.N. 
Peacekeepers and medical personnel into the enclave, which had 
been under intensive Serb attacks in recent weeks. 
  Besides Bosnia, Clinton and Papandreou also discussed 
Athens' 
relations with Turkey and the former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia. 
  For his part, Papandreou offered that Greece would lift its 
economic embargo on the land-locked Macedonia and stop blocking 
its membership in the Conference on Security and Cooperation in 
Europe (CSCE), provided that Macedonia change some articles in 
its constitution. 
  As for the Republic's name, which resembles that of the 
Greek 
province of Macedonia, Papandreou said, it would set aside for 
further negotiations. 
  Clinton, expressing understanding for Greece's "legitimate 
concerns" while calling for the end to the Greek economic 
blockade on Macedonia, said he was hopeful that an agreement 
would soon be reached. 

</TEXT>

