<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Russia Opposes NATO Air Raids on Serbs </H4>

<F P=102> OW2304031594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0257 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304031594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 22 (XINHUA) -- Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev said here today that Russia opposes the 
Bosnian Serbs' attacks on Gorazde, but NATO air strikes against 
the Serbs would escalate the violence in the former Yugoslavia. 
  Kozyrev told the INTERFAX news agency that the Serb attacks 
on Gorazde "go far beyond reasonable military necessity" and 
"the international community has the right to end the criminal 
actions." 
  However, Kozyrev said, "massive NATO air strikes, I think, 
will lead to an escalation of the conflict." 
  NATO issue an ultimatum in Brussels earlier today, ordering 
the Serbs to stop offensives against the Muslim enclave of 
Gorazde and pull their forces three kilometers away from the 
center of the town by 02:01 local time on Sunday (0001 GMT), or 
they will face NATO air raids. 
  The NATO also demanded the Serbs to grand access to the 
United Nations peacekeepers and medical teams to the embattled 
city of Goradze. 
  Russia had stressed time and again a diplomatic solution to 
the Bosnian conflicts, complaining that NATO's previous air 
strikes on the Serbs undermined the peace efforts. 

</TEXT>

