<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UN Envoy, Serbs Express `Satisfaction' </H4>

<F P=102> OW2304164794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1628 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 23 (XINHUA) -- United Nations 
Special Envoy Yasushi Akashi, Serbian President Slobodan 
Milosevic, and leader of the Bosnian Serbs Radovan Karadzic 
today expressed satisfaction with their two days of talks. 
  After their second round of talks here today on 
implementation of the cease-fire agreement in Gorazde agreed to 
on Friday [23 April] night, all three were satisfied with the 
outcome. 
  Milosevic said that the agreement was "a big step toward 
peace", adding that the Republic of Serbia would continue to 
support a peaceful solution to the Yugoslav crisis through 
negotiation. 
  Special Envoy Akashi said he believes that the agreement 
"created a possibility for avoiding a crisis". 
  Karadzic said that if peace, de-militarization and the 
elimination of the possibility of Muslim attack were achieved in 
Gorazde, a real peace could be expected. 
  At the end of 10 hours of talks on Friday, the Bosnian Serbs 
reportedly agreed to a cease-fire and the deployment of U.N. 
Protection Forces to within three kilometers around Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

