<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Serbs Continue Shelling </H4>

<F P=102> OW2304183094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1636 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 23 (XINHUA) -- Bosnian Serb Forces 
continued heavy shelling of besieged Gorazde in defiance of a 
NATO air strike ultimatum, a UN official said today in Sarajevo. 
  Dacre Holloway, UN Protection Force spokesman, was quoted as 
saying that scores of artillery and tank rounds were fired 
during "a heavy Bosnian Serb Army attack" hours before the 
deadline of 0001 GMT on Sunday [24 April] set by NATO. 
  He said the heavy artillery attack on the town began at 
11:00 
A.M. Local time, with impacts all over the city, some very 
close to U.N. military observer headquarters, and the town 
hospital was also hit again. 
  According to reports reaching here, Holloway said the Serb 
Forces were attacking from north of the Drina River which runs 
through the Muslim town. 
  He also acknowledged that there had been some Muslim firing 
but said the "indiscriminate" Serb response was out of 
proportion. 
  NATO ministers meeting Friday in Brussels ordered Bosnian 
Serb Forces to stop attacking the town immediately or face NATO 
air strikes. 
  The Serbs, who have been attacking Gorazde since March 29, 
were warned to withdraw all forces three kilometer from the 
center of the city by the Sunday deadline, and 20 kilometer from 
the town by Wednesday. 
  According to U.N. sources, about 700 people have been killed 
and more than 1,900 injured during the Serb offensive. 

</TEXT>

