<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Russian Envoy on NATO Zone Decision </H4>

<F P=102> OW2304222994 Beijing XINHUA in English 2044 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304222994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, April 23 (XINHUA) -- Russian U.N. 
Ambassador Yuliy Vorontsov today questioned NATO's decision to 
establish "military exclusion zones" around the Bosnian towns of 
Bihac, Srebrenica, Tuzla or Zepa if they were attacked. 
  "The reply goes beyond the request" of U.N. 
Secretary-General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali for air strike threats around Gorazde, 
Vorontsov told reporters after an informal Security Council 
session, which he required to convene, on possible NATO air 
strikes and the current situation around Gorazde. 
  He said his country was "in full agreement" with the U.N. 
chief's request to NATO. "We are of the opinion that the human 
tragedy at Gorazde should be stopped and if it cannot be stopped 
by political means it should be stopped by other means." 
  But he said there are some elements in NATO's decision that 
the U.N. chief did not request. There are some paragraphs of 
threat of "striking the infrastructure, striking all kinds of 
important economic areas. We do not understand why it is 
needed," he said. 
  According to NATO's North Atlantic Council decisions on 
Friday [22 April], "If any Bosnian Serb attacks involving heavy 
weapons are carried out on the U.N.-designated safe areas... 
[ellipses as received] These weapons and other Bosnian Serb 
military assets, as well as their direct and essential military 
support facilities, including but not limited to fuel 
installations and munitions sites, will be subject to NATO air 
strikes... [ellipses as received]" 
  The Russian ambassador said the Security Council would 
continue to discuss the Bosnian problem on Monday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

