<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Grachev Urges NATO To Drop Threat </H4>

<F P=102> OW2504213094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1507 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504213094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 25 (XINHUA) -- Russian Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev has urged the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organization to drop the threat of air strikes on Bosnian Serbs. 
  At a news conference, the Russian minister claimed that the 
planned NATO air attacks, especially the massive ones, can make 
the conflict uncontrollable and result in its spreading outside 
Bosnia- Herzegovina. 
  He argued that NATO air strikes did not and will not at 
present bring any results within the military sphere. 
  In Grachev's opinion, settlement of the conflict lies in a 
summit meeting involving Russia, the U.S., European Union allies 
and the United Nations, which can be held in any European state 
and should include the political leadership of the whole former 
Yugoslavia. 
  The defense minister urged the Peace-Keeping Forces in the 
Moslem-held town of Gorazde be reinforced to avert bloodshed, 
adding that Russia intends to send a 19-men strong platoon to 
the stricken city. 
  He strongly opposed the withdrawal of Russian troops from 
war- torn Bosnia-Herzegovina, warning that this would be an 
untimely and inappropriate decision fraught with a further 
political isolation of Russia in the world community. 
  Grachev said that it was not only Serbs but both conflicting 
sides who are to blame for the current crisis. 
  Gebnardt Von Moltke, NATO deputy secretary general for 
political issues, who is heading a NATO delegation participating 
in an international conference here, said earlier Monday [25 
April] that NATO is going to cooperate closely with Moscow in 
solving the Bosnian crisis. 

</TEXT>

