<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Clinton Pleased With Bosnian Cease-Fire </H4>

<F P=102> OW2604003094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1724 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604003094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 25 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton said today that he is pleased by the apparent holding of 
ceasefire around Gorazde and urged the Bosnian warring parties 
to resume peace talks. 
  "It appears that the pressure brought to bear by NATO and 
the 
U.N. is working, that the ceasefire is holding, the withdrawal 
is continuing," Clinton said. 
  "I do want to say it's now clearly time to get the 
diplomatic 
initiative going again while we maintain our vigilance," he said. 
  Meanwhile, U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher is in 
London for talks with British and French officials on the 
Bosnian situation. 
  On Tuesday [26 April], Christopher will be meeting with 
Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev before going to the 
Middle East. 
  Russian President Boris Yeltsin has proposed that Russia, 
the 
U.S., Europe and the U.N. convene a summit on Bosnia, but 
Clinton said the idea was premature although "deserves serious 
consideration." 
  "The United States won't be ready to move on a summit until 
we have a better idea what the Serbs are up to," the ASSOCIATED 
PRESS quoted an unnamed administration official as saying. 

</TEXT>

