<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Warns Bosnian Serbs of 2d Deadline </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Warns Bosnian Serbs of 2d Deadline </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604011494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1932 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604011494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, April 25 (XINHUA) -- A senior U.N. 
official warned here today that air strikes would be used 
against Bosnian Serbs if they failed to withdraw their heavy 
weapons from a 20-km exclusion zone around Gorazde by 0001 GMT 
on April 27. 
  "If they do not comply," said Kofi Annan, U.N. 
undersecretary- general, "air strikes will be used to get them 
out." 
  Subsequently, he said, the U.N. had the exclusions around 
the 
other "safe areas," which if they attempted to move heavy 
weapons in, they would also be attacked. 
  The U.N. official made these remarks at a press briefing 
held 
here this morning. 
  Annan also said that a three-km exclusion zone had been in 
effect since 0001 GMT Sunday, following a decision of the North 
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) on Friday [15 April]. 
  NATO authorized the use of air strikes against the Bosnian 
Serbs if they did not end their attacks against Gorazde, pull 
their forces back from the city center, and allow U.N. Forces 
freedom of movement there. 
  Annan said that the Bosnian Serbs had not complied promptly 
with the first deadline, but that the U.N. Protection Force 
(Unprofor) commander had decided not to use air strikes 
immediately, as it felt that progress was being made and that 
the Serbs would soon comply with the NATO ultimatum. 
  "It was important to get U.N. troops and medical units into 
the city as quickly as possible and air strikes might have 
jeopardized that operation," according to the U.N. official. 
  There are 475 U.N. personnel in Gorazde at present. 
  Answering questions on the deteriorating relations between 
the U.N. and NATO, Annan said that "the relationship is good, 
and we have excellent collaboration between the United Nations 
and the NATO." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

