<H3> <TI>   Russia Makes New Proposals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Makes New Proposals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604025194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0228 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604025194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 25 (XINHUA) -- Russia today made 
several new concrete proposals on the conflict in Bosnia, 
including the strengthening of the UN presence in the region. 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry issued a statement proposing 
the 
stabilization of order in the UN-declared "safe areas" in 
Bosnia, the INTERFAX news agency reported. 
  The statement, issued on the eve of a meeting between 
Russian 
and U.S. foreign ministers, suggests that Bosnian Serbs and 
Muslims sign an agreement on a complete cease-fire and the 
ending of hostilities. 
  A package plan for the political resolution of the Bosnian 
crisis should be sought, the Foreign Ministry announced. 
  While realistically facilitating the peace process, the 
international community should lessen its sanctions against 
Yugoslavia, the ministry said. 
  U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev are due to meet on Tuesday in 
Geneva to discuss the Bosnian crisis. 

</TEXT>

