<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   West Urged To Coordinate Monetary Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    West Urged To Coordinate Monetary Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604001994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1832 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604001994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 25 (XINHUA) -- China today called 
on the developed countries to coordinate their monetary policy 
more adequately and effectively, which it said is vital to world 
economy and trade. 
  "The asymmetrical economic cycles and adjustment pace as 
well 
as the resulting weakening coordination mechanism have weakened 
the role the industrial countries in the world economy," said 
Chen Yuan, deputy governor of People's Bank of China. 
  Speaking here today at the 42nd meeting of the Interim 
Committee of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Chen 
stressed that the developing countries have played an important 
role in helping the global economy out of its difficulties. 
  Chen said most of the developed countries, with better 
conditions of fiscal deficit and public debt, should enhance the 
underlying fiscal position to create favorable conditions for 
world economic growth. 
  Noting that many developed countries have achieved price 
stability, Chen said that these countries should take the 
domestic economic cycles into consideration while formulating 
monetary policy. 
  These countries, Chen said, "should also coordinate policies 
to avoid a recurrence of the turbulence in the international 
monetary system." 
  He said that the long-lasting structural unemployment in 
developed countries can only be addressed through reforms of the 
labor market and an acceleration of industrial restructuring in 
these countries. 
  The deputy governor of China's central bank also pointed out 
that the developed countries' reliance on protectionism to ease 
domestic economic difficulties will only prolong the structural 
adjustment process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

