<H3> <TI>   Greece `Satisfied' With Clinton's Macedonia Stance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greece `Satisfied' With Clinton's Macedonia Stance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304194994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1737 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304194994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Athens, April 23 (XINHUA) -- Greece today said it 
was satisfied with U.S. President Bill Clinton's statements on 
Macedonian issue made during a joint press conference Friday [23 
April] with Greek Premier Andreas Papandreou following their 
talks at the White House. 
  Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said that Greece 
was 
particularly satisfied with Clinton's statement on the issues of 
Macedonia, Greek-Albanian relations and the Cyprus problem. 
  Venizelos, however, expressed reservations concerning 
Clinton's optimism on Cyprus. 
  "In order to make progress in the confidence-building 
measures and the essence of the problem, we must have a 
substantial and clear change in the Turkish and Turkish-Cypriot 
stance. That is, Turkey and Turkish-Cypriot leader Rauf 
Denktash must tone down their intransigence," Venizelos said. 
  On the Macedonian issue, the spokesman said that "It is 
important that President Clinton acknowledges Greek 
sensitivities, the soundness of Greece's position, and places 
such great emphasis on the mission of UN Special Mediator Cyrus 
Vance and Clinton's special envoy Matthew Nimetz." 
  Referring to the meeting on Monday between Greek Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias and Vance, the spokesman said that 
"We must be patient and restrained... [ellipses as received]." 

</TEXT>

