<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industrial Countries Urged To Help Alleviate World Poverty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Industrial Countries Urged To Help Alleviate World Poverty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2404164494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1621 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2404164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 24 (XINHUA) -- China urged the 
industrial countries here today to take concrete actions to help 
the developing countries alleviate their poverty and improve 
their economies. 
  "We urge the developed countries to take concrete actions to 
meet the target of 0.7 percent of gross domestic product set by 
the U.N." and use the fund to help the developing world, said 
Chen Yuan, deputy governor of the People's Bank of China. 
  In this aspect, Chen said at the 50th meeting of the Group 
of 
24 Ministers, the developed countries have "an unavoidable 
responsibility". 
  "With the developed and developing countries' increasing 
interdependence, it is clear that not until most of the 
developing countries have achieved stable and sustainable growth 
can sound and sustained global development be attained," Chen 
said. 
  The deputy governor of China's central bank said that a 
serious difficulty for developing countries' economic 
development was the uncertainty for their external environment. 
  It included the persistent decline in commodity prices, 
various forms of trade protectionism and the heavy debt burden 
which he said imposed acute constraints on the economic 
development of many low- income developing countries. 
  "We urge the developed countries to persevere in 
substantially reducing the debt of the low-income developing 
countries," he stressed. 
  He also urged the developed countries to take more 
substantive action in the areas of finance and technical 
assistance as well as in facilitating an improved economic 
environment. 
  Speaking of the world economy, Chen said the global economic 
activity is expected to improve in the next two years, although 
continuing recession in most European countries and Japan 
remains a cause for concern. 
  Many developing countries, he said, continue to face severe 
difficulties in their economic development, while economies in 
most East European countries and the countries of the former 
Soviet Union are still enduring hardships. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

