<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiang Zemin Meets Governor-General </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jiang Zemin Meets Governor-General </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504152894 Beijing XINHUA in Chinese 1344 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 25 (XINHUA) -- Chinese President 
Jiang Zemin, in a meeting with visiting Canadian 
Governor-General Ramon John Hnatyshyn here today, expressed hope 
that China and Canada would strengthen friendly exchanges and 
cooperation. 
  He added that, in the fundamental interest of the two 
countries and the two peoples, bilateral relations should be 
raised to a new stage of overall cooperation, on the basis of 
seeking common ground while reserving differences, mutual 
respect, equality and mutual benefit. 
  Extending his warm welcome to Hnatyshyn, Jiang said that in 
the 20 years of diplomatic relations between the two countries, 
bilateral relations have witnessed fruitful development in all 
fields. 
  "We are pleased to see that during the past few years, China 
and Canada have overcome the temporary difficulties in bilateral 
relations under joint efforts and restored the vigorous 
development of such relations," the Chinese president said. 
  Jiang said that he had very good talks with Canadian Prime 
Minister Jean Chretien when they met in Seattle in November last 
year, noting that Chinese Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua is in Canada 
on a visit now. 
  He pointed out that "to enhance exchanges between leaders of 
the two countries is of great significance." 
  It is learned that this is the first visit to China by a 
Canadian governor-general since 1987, and a senior Chinese 
diplomat here pointed out that Hnatyshyn's visit marks the 
resumption of political contacts between leaders of the two 
countries and the overall normalization of Sino-Canadian 
relations. 
  On bilateral economic and trade relations, Jiang said that 
the two economies are highly complementary, and Canada has 
become one of China's major trade partners in the world. 
  He continued that bilateral trade volume has grown by a 
large 
margin and that two-way investment and economic and 
technological cooperation have been continuously broadened. 
  Jiang noted that Canada has valuable expertise in 
communications, telecommunications and hydropower, which are 
being emphasized in China's development for the next few years. 
  He said that China's economy is in rapid and sustained 
growth, the market is expanding and the investment environment 
is becoming better, which provides good opportunities for the 
expansion of Sino-Canadian mutually beneficial cooperation. 
  He asked his guest to urge the Canadian Government to seize 
the opportunities so as to further bilateral economic and trade 
cooperation. 
  Hnatyshyn expressed his pleasure at visiting China, adding 
that bilateral relations date back to a long time ago and his 
current visit marks the further development of such relations. 
  He said that "we admire China's achievement in its economic 
reform and believe that the Chinese people will have a better 
future." 
  He noted that China is more and more important in the world, 
and Canada is ready to strengthen cooperation bilaterally, 
multi-laterally and in international affairs, so as to 
continuously promote relations between the two countries. 
  On the human rights issue, Hnatyshyn expressed his 
understanding of China's domestic conditions, stressing that the 
human rights issue should not be linked to trade. 
  He pointed out that Canada is willing to carry out 
discussions and cooperation with China on this issue. 
  During the one-hour meeting, Jiang also briefed Hnatyshyn on 
China's economic development. 
  Present at the meeting were Wang Bingqian, vice chairman of 
the National People's Congress Standing Committee; He Luli, vice 
chairman of the central committee of the Revolutionary Committee 
of the Chinese Kuomintang; Sun Yongfu, chairman of the reception 
committee and vice minister of railways; and Jiang Enzhu, vice 
minister of foreign affairs. Present at the meeting on the 
Canadian side was Canadian Minister of Agriculture and Agri-Food 
Ralph Goodale who was accompanying the Governor-General on the 
trip. 
  Hnatyshyn arrived here at noon today on a state visit to 
China. 
  This afternoon, President Jiang hosted a grand welcoming 
ceremony for Hnatyshyn on the plaza outside the east entrance of 
the Great Hall of the People 
  Before the welcoming ceremony, Governor-General Hnatyshyn 
visited the Forbidden City. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

