<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zou Jiahua Meets With Canada's MacLaren </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zou Jiahua Meets With Canada's MacLaren </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2404222594 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0846 
GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2404222594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Toronto, 22 Apr (XINHUA) -- When Roy MacLaren, 
Canadian International Trade Minister, held talks with Zou 
Jiahua, visiting Chinese State Council Vice Premier, in Toronto 
on 22 April, he said that he had just returned from a visit to 
China and that China's rapid economic development had left a 
deep impression on him. He said he was convinced Canada and 
China could become very good cooperative partners. 
  MacLaren also reaffirmed support for the restoration of 
China's status as a signatory state of GATT and for China's 
becoming a founding member of the World Trade Organization. 
  Zou Jiahua said he had personally experienced the strong 
desire of the Canadian Government and personalities of Canada's 
various circles to strengthen cooperation with China in the past 
few days of his Canada visit. He said he thought the two 
countries already had the conditions for accelerating the 
development of their bilateral relations and that the 
opportunity is also very favorable. 
  MacLaren and Zou Jiahua jointly explored the prospects for 
Sino- Canadian trade and cooperation in science and technology. 
Both sides believed that, though Sino-Canadian trade and 
economic relations have enjoyed comparatively great development 
in recent years, much remains to be desired when compared with 
the actual needs and existing potentials of the two countries. 
The potentials for the two countries to expand cooperation in 
energy, transportation, hydroelectric power, communications, and 
other infrastructure fields are still very tremendous. Both 
sides discussed relevant specific issues and reached a consensus 
on a wide range of topics. 
  After their talks ended, MacLaren hosted a banquet in honor 
of Zou Jiahua and his party in the evening. 

</TEXT>

