<H3> <TI>   Zou Tours Nuclear Power Plant </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zou Tours Nuclear Power Plant </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2404222894 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0855 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2404222894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Toronto, 21 Apr (XINHUA) -- Vice Premier Zou 
Jiahua, who was paying a visit to Canada, toured the Darlington 
Nuclear Power Plant on 21 April. 
  Zou Jiahua arrived in Toronto on 20 April after visiting 
Vancouver. The Darlington Nuclear Power Plant was the first 
stop of the tour arranged for him in Toronto. Strichter, chief 
of the nuclear power plant, told Zou Jiahua that he hoped to see 
Canadian built nuclear power plants equipped with heavy-water 
reactors in China. 
  Strichter enthusiastically recommended Canada's heavy-water 
reactor technology to the Chinese guests. He said: Canada's 
heavy- water reactors are one of the world's recognized high 
technologies. Since they use natural uranium as fuel, they not 
only cost less than reactors using enriched uranium, but are 
also safer. In addition, Canada uses the parallel connection 
technology so that nuclear power plants will not have to stop 
operation while having their old nuclear fuel pellets replaced 
with new ones. Canada currently owns 22 reactors; all of them 
have adopted heavy-water reactor technology. 
  After his tour of the Darlington Nuclear Power Plant, Zou 
Jiahua was received by Ontario Province Governor Ray [name as 
received]. On the afternoon of the same day, he also visited the 
Spa Aircraft Company [name as received]. In the evening, the 
Canadian-Chinese Trade Council held a banquet in his honor. 

</TEXT>

