<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Release on Border Talks With India </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Press Release on Border Talks With India </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2504125294 Delhi ISI Diplomatic Information Service in 
English 1155 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2504125294 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi ISI Diplomatic Information Service </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press release" -- issuing agency, place, date not given] </F>
  [Text] 1. The second meeting of the India-China expert 
group was held in Beijing on April 21-22, 1994. The Indian 
delegation, which was led by Shivshankar Menon, joint secretary 
(North East) in Ministry of External Affairs, included 
representatives from the Ministries of External Affairs, Defense 
and Home Affairs, the Army Headquarters and the Survey of India. 
The Chinese delegation, led by Mr. Fu Xuezhang, deputy director 
Asian Department, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, also comprised of 
experts from their concerned departments. 
  2. The expert group reviewed the progress made at its first 
meeting held in New Delhi in February 1994 and continued 
deliberations on the tasks assigned to it under the agreement on 
the maintenance of peace and tranquility along the Line of 
Actual Control [LAC] in the India-China border areas. The 
mandate of the expert group includes assisting the Joint Working 
Group in clarification of the Line of Actual Control between 
India and China, redeployment of military forces along the LAC, 
other confidence building measures and verification methods. 
  3. At the second meeting, the two sides reached agreement on 
the work regulations of the expert group. This document, which 
spells out the mandate, future tasks and modalities of the 
expert group, was signed by the leaders of the two delegations 
on April 22, 1994. 
  4. Both sides also noted with satisfaction that the 
situation along the India-China LAC was peaceful. They also 
expressed satisfaction at the confidence building measures 
already in place between them and exchanged views on further 
such measures as envisaged in the agreement establishing the 
expert group. They also had in-depth discussions on urgent 
questions relating to the maintenance of peace and tranquility 
in border areas. 
  5. Both sides adopted a constructive and forward-looking 
approach in these discussions which were held in a friendly 
atmosphere. 
  6. It was agreed that the next meeting of the India-China 
expert group will be held in New Delhi around end of 1994. This 
meeting will be preceded by the seventh meeting of the 
India-China Joint Working Group in Beijing around the middle of 
1994. 

</TEXT>

