<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Official Says Lu Ping, Patten Have `Nothing' To Discuss </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Official Says Lu Ping, Patten Have `Nothing' To Discuss </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2604053694 Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS in English 26 Apr 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> HK2604053694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Rain Ren] </F>
  [Text] An official from the local office of the New China 
News Agency (Xinhua) has reconfirmed there was no chance that Lu 
Ping, the director of the State Council's Hong Kong and Macao 
Affairs Office, would meet the Governor during his visit to the 
territory next week. It would be Lu's first visit since Chris 
Patten took office. Patten has said he would be "delighted" to 
talk to Lu. 
  "Patten probably thinks that he can do whatever he wants," 
said the local Xinhua deputy director, Zhang Junsheng. "He 
thinks if he wants to meet Lu, he can do so at any time. It is 
just his wishful thinking." When asked why Lu should decline 
Patten's invitation, Zhang said no reason was needed. "It is 
him (Patten) who has undermined the cooperative spirits of the 
two countries. 
  "Now Britain's Foreign Affairs Select Committee report 
publicly voices its support for Patten's so-called reform 
proposal. 
  "There is nothing Lu can talk to him (about)." 
  Sir Robin McLaren, Britain's ambassador to Beijing, said 
yesterday the report represented the views of some MPs, not the 
British government. 

</TEXT>

