<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Deny Hong Kong SAR To Reinstate Death Penalty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials Deny Hong Kong SAR To Reinstate Death Penalty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2604053894 Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS in English 26 Apr 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> HK2604053894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong EASTERN EXPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Rain Ren] </F>
  [Text] China has denied a report suggesting that capital 
punishment would be restored in Hong Kong after 1997. The 
report in The Sunday Times quoted Zhang Rongshun, from the State 
Council's Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office, saying that the 
future Special Administrative Region (SAR) government might 
restore the death penalty. But Zhang said: "I did not say 
there was such a possibility. I just said it was for the SAR 
government to decide whether there was a need to restore the 
death penalty in Hong Kong." 
  Zhang Junsheng, the deputy director of the local office of 
the New China News Agency (Xinhua), agreed. "What he said means 
that it is a decision to be made by the SAR instead of the 
central government," Zhang Junsheng said. "Of course, it cannot 
be said that the death penalty can never be used in Hong Kong." 
  Simon Li, a retired high court judge and leader of the legal 
sub- group of the Preliminary Working Committee, said the death 
penalty was not discussed by the PWC. "I personally don't think 
it really matters whether or not Hong Kong should have capital 
punishment after 1997," Li said yesterday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

