<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Further Steps' To Be Taken in Fiscal, Tax Reforms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Further Steps' To Be Taken in Fiscal, Tax Reforms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604001594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1737 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604001594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 25 (XINHUA) -- China said today 
that it will take further steps to reform the country's fiscal 
and tax systems, the financial sector, foreign trade, investment 
and the state-owned enterprises. 
  Chen Yuan, deputy governor of the People's Bank of China, 
China's central bank, said here today that introduction of a new 
tax system and the unification of exchanges rates early this 
year have proved "satisfactory". 
  "The Chinese Government is well aware that many problems in 
the areas of macroeconomic management and the industrial 
structure remain unsolved," Chen said at the 42nd meeting of the 
Interim Committee of the International Monetary Fund (IMF). 
  Chen said budgetary revenue of China increased by 21.4 
percent in the first quarter of this year, compared with the 
same period last year, and the exchange rate of renminbi, 
China's currency, has remained stable. 
  "The Chinese Government is fully confident that in pushing 
ahead with reforms it will achieve its objectives while 
maintaining macroeconomic stability," Chen stressed. 

</TEXT>

