<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Worker Average Per Capita Income Increased </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Worker Average Per Capita Income Increased </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504104194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0752 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 25 (XINHUA) -- Last year the average 
per capita income of Chinese workers was 3,236 yuan, up 19.4 
percent over the previous year. 
  This was revealed by the China Labor Development Communique, 
jointly issued here today by the Labor Ministry and Statistics 
Bureau. 
  Liu Guanxue, spokesman for the Labor Ministry, quoted the 
communique as saying that in 1993 the country's total payroll 
reached a record 477 billion yuan, a rise of 21.1 percent over 
1992. After allowing for price rises, the actual increases in 
the workers' total payroll and their average per capita annual 
income were 4.3 percent and 2.8 percent, respectively. 
  The spokesman attributed the rise to the reform of 
enterprise 
operational mechanism and to the ongoing reform of the state's 
wage distribution system, which now cover 18,000 enterprises and 
14 million workers across the country. 
  An elastic wage plan, the core of the current wage 
distribution reform, has been carried out in 30 provinces, 
autonomous regions and municipalities. The plan is designed to 
set the total payrolls in light of the economic efficiency 
targets of various localities. 

</TEXT>

