<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rules on Conversion to Share Companies Published </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rules on Conversion to Share Companies Published </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2504143794 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in English 1113 
GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2504143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 25 (CNS) -- China has recently made 
known regulations governing conversion of state assets into 
shares in a bid to meet the needs of reform of the enterprise 
system, especially the changing of state-owned medium- and 
large-sized enterprises into shareholding companies. The 
regulations stress that the overall restructuring of state-owned 
enterprises into shareholding companies had first to be subject 
to evaluation of their assets and prior approval was a must. 
  The regulations state that before the issuing of new shares, 
the adjusted net assets book value of a particular enterprise 
had first of all to be converted into the stake held by 
shareholders. Should part of the assets not be turned into 
shares, it would be listed in a capital accumulation fund and 
the capital would in no way be changed into liabilities. 
  The matter of whether the ratio which the conversion of 
assets into shares will employ is suitable has to be considered 
together with the proposal for the issuing of shares and the 
issuing price. The premium price for the issuing of new shares 
should not be kept too low, otherwise the net assets book value 
will not be fully shown. 
  The regulations also stress that the premium price should be 
made higher in order to fully reflect the actual value of the 
stake resulting from the conversion of state-owned assets into 
shares. 

</TEXT>

