<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seventeen Cities Chosen as Urban Reform Models </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seventeen Cities Chosen as Urban Reform Models </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2304080394 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 23 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK2304080394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sun Shangwu: "Model Cities Set For Urban Reform"] </F>
  [Text] The central government has selected 17 cities to 
carry out "comprehensive urban reforms' and serve as national 
models for how to develop a socialist market system. 
  The reform package is designed to push forward urban reform 
in a comprehensive manner, instead of focusing on only the 
business sector, said Guo Shuqing, director of the Comprehensive 
Department under the State Commission for Restructuring the 
Economic System yesterday in Beijing. 
  The pilot cities include Changchun, Harbin, Anshan and 
Shenyang in Northeast China; Tianjin, Tangshan. Xian and Yantai 
in North China: Nanjing, Ningbo, Tongling and Changzhou in East 
China; Wuhan in Central China; Chengdu and Chongqing in 
Southwest China; and Quanzhou and Guangzhou in South China. 
  The reforms to be implemented in these cities will focus on 
three areas this year. 
  First is the reform of the property ownership system to 
transform State-owned enterprises into modern corporations. 
This effort will go hand-in-hand with developing the finance, 
real estate, labour and technology markets, the official said. 
  The second area will be the improvement of the pension and 
unemployment insurance systems. At the same time, housing 
reform will be hastened by selling houses, raising rents and 
building more houses for ordinary salary-earners. 
  Thirdly, education, science and technology will be reformed 
in line with the development of a market economy. 
  The pilot cities are also encouraged to move faster to 
reform 
government functions. 
  Guo stressed that these cities will not enjoy any 
preferential treatment. 
  "Preferential policies are counter to the idea of a market 
economy, which requires competition on equal footing and 
adherence to international practices," he said. 
  The 17 cities are located not only in the rich eastern 
provinces, but are also in the relatively poor central and 
western provinces. 
  "The purpose of this drive is to speed up reforms in inland 
cities and help them get rid of poverty," Guc added. 
  Guo's commission will be responsible for designing standards 
for the model reforms and it plans to set up a liaison 
association for mayors of these pilot cities, which is expected 
to give them chance to exchange information on their reform 
experiences. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

