<F P=100> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> East Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai's Pudong Area Reports Increased Foreign Trade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai's Pudong Area Reports Increased Foreign Trade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604011794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0021 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604011794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, April 26 (XINHUA) -- The Pudong New Area 
in Shanghai, the largest economic development zone in China, 
reported an import and export volume of 575 million U.S. dollars 
in the first quarter of this year, a 128.17 percent increase 
over the same period of last year, according to the latest 
information from Shanghai customs. 
  The area registered an import value of 305 million U.S. 
dollars, an increase of 132.8 percent; and an export value of 
270 million U.S. dollars, an increase of 123.1 percent, 
according to the customs office. 
  The number of countries and regions having trade relations 
with the area has grown from 106 in the corresponding period of 
last year to 136. Some developed countries have become major 
trade partners of the area. 
  In the first quarter of this year, the area had a trade 
value 
of 151 million U.S. dollars with Japan, an increase of 118 
percent over the same period of last year; a trade value of 117 
million U.S. dollars with European Community countries, an 
increase of 148 percent; a trade value of 75 million U.S. 
dollars with the United States, an increase of 188 percent; and 
a trade value of 52 million U.S. dollars with Hong Kong, an 
increase of 108 percent. 
  Foreign-funded enterprises have become a major force behind 
the development of the area's foreign trade. In 1993, they 
reported an import and export value of more than one billion 
U.S. dollars, 41 percent of the area's total. 
  In addition, entrepot trade in the area, which is a bonded 
zone, is booming. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

