<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei To Protest Name Change in ADB Forum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei To Protest Name Change in ADB Forum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504092694 Taipei CNA in English 0807 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Debbie Kuo] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 25 (CNA) -- The Republic of China 
[ROC] will again protest the Asian Development Bank's (ADB) 
unilateral decision to change the ROC's title at the 
international banking institute to "Taipei, China." 
  Vice Finance Minister Li Chung-ying, who will lead an ROC 
delegation to the 27th ADB board of directors meeting scheduled 
to open May 3 in Nice, France, said the name change was 
unacceptable and unjust. 
  The unilateral decision to change the name deprived the ROC, 
an ADB founder, of its rights at the international banking 
institution, Li said. 
  Li said he may issue the protest during the meeting either 
directly to the ADB board chairman, or in a statement when he 
makes an oral report. 
  The ADB changed Taiwan's representative name from Chinese, 
Taipei into "Taipei, China" after Beijing joined the group in 
1986. Taipei refused to take part in any ADB activities in 
protest of the insensitive and unfair treatment in 1986 and 1987. 
  Taipei resumed its involvement with the ADB and returned to 
the annual board meeting in 1988 after President Li Teng-hui 
advocated more pragmatic diplomatic measures. 
  The ROC mission protested the name change during a board 
meeting last year by placing a sign reading "under protest" 
above the "Taipei, China" designation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

