<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   KMT Central Committee Meets on Constitutional Changes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KMT Central Committee Meets on Constitutional Changes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304150894 Taipei CNA in English 1337 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304150894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 23 (CNA) -- The ruling Kuomintang 
began a special meeting of its Central Committee on Saturday [23 
April] to consider constitutional-amendment proposals prepared 
by a party task force. 
  The proposals are expected to be endorsed by the committee, 
thus paving the way for some key changes in Taiwan's political 
operations. Associate members of the committee and ranking 
party officials are also attending the meeting to air their 
views. 
  The meeting, which will conclude Sunday, is being held at 
the 
Chungshan Building in Yangmingshan, a Taipei suburb. 
  Speaking at the opening ceremony in his capacity as KMT 
chairman, Republic of China [ROC] President Li Teng-hui 
reiterated his idea of a country run by the people. "This is a 
meeting to tell the people of the nation the ruling party's 
determination to push ahead with constitutional reforms so as to 
realize the idea of, 'the power belongs to the whole of the 
people.'" 
  He urged the committee members to build consensus during the 
meeting so as to help accomplish the mission of constitutional 
reform. 
  If endorsed by the meeting, the proposals will be formally 
submitted to the National Assembly, which is scheduled to 
convene later this month. 
  In the draft proposals, the KMT will recommend several key 
changes, including election of the president and vice president 
by popular vote, rather than by members of the National 
Assembly, as has been done in the past; installment of a speaker 
and vice speaker in the National Assembly; and a restriction on 
the premier's right to co-sign the laws promulgated and mandates 
issued by the president. 
  The ruling party will also seek to extend the legislative 
term from three years to four, [words indistinct] limit 
legislator, right of immunity from prosecution for speeches 
delivered during legislative sessions, and to change the 
official name of the "Shanpao (mountain) people" to "aborigines." 

</TEXT>

