<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei To Sign GATT Government Procurement Agreements </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei To Sign GATT Government Procurement Agreements </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304112394 Taipei CNA in English 0754 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304112394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y.C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 23 (CNA) -- Taiwan has decided to 
sign government procurement agreements with contracting parties 
of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) this year 
in order to facilitate its entry into the Geneva-based world 
trade regulating body. 
  The cabinet-level GATT task force gave the green light to 
the 
plan late Friday [22 April]. The task force comprises officials 
from the Council for Economic Planning and Development and the 
Ministry of Economic Affairs. 
  Previously, Taiwan rejected such agreements because of the 
great number of state organizations involved. 
  Although the government agreed to the plan, it will seek to 
exclude the International Telecommunications Administration, 
Taiwan Power Company, Chinese Petroleum Corp., and China Steel 
Corp. from the procurement agreements, informed sources said. 
  Abrupt market opening might trigger unfair competition and 
thus adversely affect these state-run companies, the sources 
noted. 
  Under the new plan, they pointed out, the government will 
substantially revise its current procurement practices to come 
into line with the GATT codes. 
  For example, they elaborated, the base price for open 
tenders 
will be lowered from the current NT$ [New Taiwan dollars] 50 
million (U.S.$1.88 million) to NT$4.7 million (U.S.$177,000). 
  Moreover, all the bidding procedures will be completely open 
and transparent, they said. 
  Taiwan, which was accepted as a GATT observer in September 
1992, hopes to become a full member by the end of this year. 
All GATT signatories are set to become members of the World 
Trade Organization, which will be given tougher enforcement 
powers to supersede GATT and will start operations between 
January and July next year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-3952 </DOCNO>
