<H3> <TI>   Iran Demands Taiwan Bank Return Arms Sale Money </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iran Demands Taiwan Bank Return Arms Sale Money </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304042494 Taipei Voice of Free China in English 0200 GMT 
22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2304042494 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei Voice of Free China </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News" program] </F>
  [Text] Two former Iranian military officials have demanded 
at a court hearing that a Taiwan state-run bank return $15 
million that Iran paid for arms that were never delivered. The 
mysterious arms deal began in 1991 when Iran transferred the 
money to a Midland Bank in London to the Taiwan Changhua 
Commercial Bank [sentence as heard]. Iran had wanted to buy 
bullets and other like ammunition from Taiwan's arms dealers for 
use in its eight-year war against Iraq, which ended with a cease 
fire in August 1988. But the Taipei government later turned 
down the sale. 
  (Aduba Hatami) and (Motosher Fatayi) told the Taiwan High 
Court they came to Taiwan in 1981 with another defense ministry 
official but the Taiwan bank rejected their demand for the 
money. The bank said that the money already had been withdrawn 
by three men presenting passports bearing the names of the 
Iranian officials listed by the Midland Bank as the recipients. 
Iran's Defense Ministry filed a lawsuit in the Taipei District 
Court to reclaim the amount. The Changhua Bank argued that its 
clients had been the Midland Bank, not the Iranian Government. 
The local high court did not say when it would deliver its 
final verdict. 

</TEXT>

