<H3> <TI>   German Minister Supports Taiwan GATT Bid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    German Minister Supports Taiwan GATT Bid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604082594 Taipei CNA in English 0714 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604082594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 26 (CNA) -- German Economic Affairs 
Minister Guenter Rexrodt said Monday [25 April] that he supports 
Taiwan's accession to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade 
(GATT). 
  Speaking upon arrival at Chiang Kai-shek International 
Airport, Rexrodt also said he is visiting Taiwan to help 
strengthen bilateral economic and trade relations. 
  Rexrodt arrived in Taiwan late Monday night at the the head 
of an eight-member delegation. He was met at the airport by 
Economic Affairs Minister P.K. Chiang. 
  Meanwhile, Rexrodt met with Minister of Transportation and 
Communications Liu Chao-shiu on Tuesday to lobby for German 
companies seeking contracts to build Taiwan's proposed 
high-speed railway project. 
  During a meeting with Vice Economic Affairs Minister Hsu 
Kai- 
sheng later in the day, Rexrodt and Hsu discussed the signing of 
a bilateral agreement to avoid double taxation. 
  Hsu said he hopes germany can remove Taiwan from the "high 
tension area" list which Germany uses to prohibit arms sales to 
designated countries. 
  Rexrodt said Germany welcomes Taiwan investment in eastern 
Germany and the establishment of a Taiwan Trade Center in 
Frankfurt to promote bilateral ties. 
  Two-way trade between Taiwan and Germany totaled U.S.$7.73 
billion in 1993 with Germany enjoying a trade surplus of 
U.S.$715 million. Germany is Taiwan's largest trade partner in 
Europe. 
  Rexrodt is scheduled to leave Taipei Tuesday night. 

</TEXT>

