<H3> <TI>   Taipei, Philippines Agree on Tariff Reductions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei, Philippines Agree on Tariff Reductions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504134894 Taipei CNA in English 1305 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Timothy Sun and Y.C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Manila, April 25 (CNA) -- Taiwan on Monday [25 
April] pledged to reduce import duties on Philippine products by 
an average 18 percent during the first year of its entry into 
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  The commitment was made after just three hours of tariff- 
reduction negotiations with the Philippines held at the Ministry 
of Industry and Commerce in Manila. 
  Lin Yi-fu, deputy director-general of Taiwan's Board of 
Foreign Trade, headed a 13-member delegation at the meeting. 
  Lin said the meeting was harmonious, and that the two sides 
agreed to hold further consultations to work out details of the 
agreement. 
  This was Taiwan's first tariff-reduction meeting with any 
Southeast Asian country. Taiwan has held similar negotiations 
with Australia, [words indistinct], New Zealand, South Africa, 
Turkey, and the United States. 
  Lin and his delegation will travel to Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia 
Tuesday to conduct similar talks with Malaysia. 
  Bilateral tariff-reduction talks with GATT contacting 
parties 
are expected to help ensure Taiwan's smooth accession to the 
Geneva- based world trade regulating body. 
  Taiwan, which was accepted as a GATT observer in September 
1992, hopes to become a full member by the end of the year. 

</TEXT>

