<H3> <TI>   South African Envoy Opens `One-Day Vote' in Taipei 26 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    South African Envoy Opens `One-Day Vote' in Taipei 26 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604090194 Taipei CNA in English 0737 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604090194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Y.C. Tsai] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 26 (CNA) -- J.L. Viljoen, South 
Africa's ambassador to the Republic of China [ROC], opened 
Taiwan voting in his country's first all-race elections when he 
cast his ballot at 7 a.m. 
  All citizens and permanent residents of South Africa above 
the age of 18 residing or traveling here are eligible to vote at 
Taipei's polling station, Viljoen said. 
  The polling station, located at the South African Embassy on 
Tinhua North Road, will remain open until 7 p.m. Tuesday [26 
April], he added. 
  Although a few hundred South Africans have already cast 
their 
ballots, the envoy said he did not know how many voters will 
turn out for the one-day vote. 
  In order to ensure the poll's fairness, the South African 
government invited Chou Nien-tzu, a researcher at National 
Chengchi University's Institute of International Relations, and 
Arlene Lang, a U.S. citizen, to act as observers at the Taipei 
polling station. 
  All the ballot boxes will be sealed and transported back to 
South Africa via express delivery for vote counting, which will 
begin on April 29, Viljoen said. 
  The South African polls, which will elect the president, 
National Assembly, nine governors, and nine regional assemblies, 
opened Tuesday morning and will continue through April 28. 

</TEXT>

