<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Reports Developments on Bosnia-Herzegovina </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UN Council Demands Cease-Fire </H4>

<F P=102> OW2204144694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1321 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, April 21 (XINHUA) -- The United 
Nations Security Council today demanded an immediate cease-fire 
by the Bosnian Serbs, under the auspices of the UN Protection 
Force (Unprofor), in Gorazde and throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The council, by adopting this resolution, invited the 
secretary- general to take the steps necessary to ensure that 
Unprofor is able to monitor the situation in Gorazde, one of the 
six UN-designated "safe havens" in the republic. 
  Condemning in the strongest terms the shelling and attacks 
by 
Bosnian Serb forces against Gorazde over the past two weeks, the 
council demanded the withdrawal of these forces and their 
weapons to a distance where they no longer constitute a threat 
to the safe area. 
  The council also demanded the immediate release of all UN 
personnel currently held by the Bosnian Serb forces, as well as 
unimpeded freedom of movement for Unprofor in the fulfillment of 
its tasks. 
  In order to bring together current diplomatic initiatives, 
the council called for the intensification of efforts to achieve 
a peaceful settlement, with coordination and close consultation 
between representatives of the United States and Russia and 
those of the United Nations and the European Union. 
  The council warned that it "stands ready promptly to 
consider 
taking further measures as required." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

