<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Receives Steed as Gift in Bishkek </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Peng Receives Steed as Gift in Bishkek </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604055194 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1020 
GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2604055194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Tidbit" by reporters Zhou Shuchun (0719 2885 2504) and Hu </F>
Xiaoguang (5170 2556 0342): "At the Foot of Lofty Tianshan, a 
Fine Steed Conveys Friendship"] 
  [Text] Bishkek, 24 Apr (XINHUA) -- On 24 April, Kyrgyz 
Prime Minister Dzhumagulov handed the reins of a tall, deep 
brown steed strapped with saddle and stirrups into the hands of 
Premier Li Peng at the foot of the lofty Tianshan. 
  Today is the third day of Li Peng's visit to Kyrgyzstan. In 
a most solemn ceremony of the Kyrgyz nationality held at a 
national park famous for its "multicolored dragon spruces," 
Dzhumagulov offered this fine-bred steed as a present to Premier 
Li Peng to show respect and friendship for the Chinese people. 
The horse is named after a Kyrgyz river called "Naolusi" [name 
as received]. It is also the name of a traditional festival of 
the Kyrgyz nationality, meaning "the beginning of spring." 
  The horse, 1.7 meters tall and over 2 meters long, is six 
years old. It won a horse race at Bishkek last year. When the 
Chinese premier approached the fine steed, it raised its head 
and neighed. Softly touching the steed's long mane, Li Peng said 
laughingly: "It is very friendly." 
  On a slope at an altitude of 2,000 meters above sea level 
and 
against a backdrop of mountains whose peaks are perennially 
covered with snow, Li Peng and his wife Zhu Lin gladly posed for 
a group photo with Kyrgyz girls and boys singing a song in front 
of a forest of multicolored, evergreen dragon spruces at the 
foot of the mountain. 
  Chinese Ambassador to Kyrgyzstan Pan Zhanlin told reporters 
Premier Li Peng has entrusted the raising of the fine steed 
symbolizing the spring of Sino-Kyrgyz friendship to the Ili Army 
Horse Ranch in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, which borders 
Kyrgyzstan. 

</TEXT>

