<F P=100> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Southwest Region Expands Economic Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Southwest Region Expands Economic Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2604033694 Chengdu Sichuan People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 2300 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2604033694 </F>
<F P=104>  Chengdu Sichuan People's Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sichuan, Yunnan, and Guizhou Provinces, Guangxi and 
Tibet Autonomous Regions, and the cities of Chengdu and 
Chongqing have joined together to explore the market, thus 
enabling the great southwest to march toward the new market 
structure with giant strides. 
  The southwest is one of the areas in China with the greatest 
potential for economic growth. Nevertheless, the southwest's 
per capita gross industrial and agricultural output value was 
lower than that of other parts of the country by 320 yuan in the 
early 1980's. Since early 1984, after the southwest economic 
cooperation program was initiated, the great southwest has been 
rising rapidly as a new power in the market. In 1993, the 
area's gross industrial and agricultural output value increased 
by more than 230 percent over 1983. Nowadays, the southwest has 
become one of the areas in China with the greatest economic 
vitality. 
  Over the past 10 years, the five provinces and autonomous 
regions and the two cities have lifted restrictions one after 
another, removed barriers between them, and opened their own 
markets to each other. As a result, more than 6,000 economic 
cooperation projects were started. In the field of 
communications and telecommunications, all the parties of the 
southwest have joined to raise funds totaling more than 200 
million yuan to build trans- provincial highways with a total 
length of 918 km, four cross-river bridges linking Sichuan 
Province with other provinces and regions, and opened more than 
100 province-wide passenger transport routes. With the support 
of all parties, the electrification projects for the 
Chengdu-Chongqing, Guiyang-Kunming, and Chongqing-Guiyang 
railways were completed ahead of schedule. The key postal and 
telecommunication facility projects and microwave 
telecommunication centers of such central cities as Chengdu, 
Chongqing, and Kunming, as well as the Tibet satellite 
telecommunication station, have been put into operation. 
Members of the southwest have also made major progress in their 
joint efforts to explore energy resources. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-3973 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi080_v_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-080 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Patrol Boats Arrive at Largest Spratly Island </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Patrol Boats Arrive at Largest Spratly Island </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604095394 Taipei Voice of Free China in English 0200 GMT 
26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2604095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei Voice of Free China </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Taiwan police on Sunday [24 April] set foot on the 
largest island in the Spratly Island chain for the first time in 
ROC [Republic of China] history. Local media described the move 
as an affirmation of the ROC's exclusive and complete control 
over the island in the South China Sea. 
  More than 30 police officers from the National Police 
Administration escorted the Council of Agriculture research 
vessel to Taiping Island and then visited the ROC marines posted 
there. This was the first time the National Police 
Administration has sent officers to the island. It was part of 
a wider plan to bring the Spratly further under ROC control. 
  The ROC is maintaining a radar station, meteorological 
center, power plant, library, and marine activities center on 
the island. Vietnam, the Philippines, Brunei, mainland China, 
Malaysia, and Taiwan all claim part or all of the Spratlys. All 
except Brunei have troops stationed on the islands. 

</TEXT>

