<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Cites Christopher's Warning to Bosnian Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Cites Christopher's Warning to Bosnian Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604231894 Beijing XINHUA in English 2249 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604231894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] London, April 26 (XINHUA) -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher said today that Bosnian Serbs must do more to 
avert the threat of NATO air strikes. 
  Speaking to reporters after talks with British Foreign 
Secretary Douglas Hurd, Christopher said the Serbs had not yet 
done enough to avoid the threat of being bombed. 
  "The information I have this morning is that the Serbs have 
moved a number of heavy weapons outside the 20 km zone, but 
there are a number still there," he said. 
  "It is clear that today will be an important day to see if 
they really will comply with requirements," he stressed. 
  Hurd also told reporters that he hoped the Serbs would pull 
back completely. 
  "If they don't then they know there will be air strikes 
against them," he warned. 
  Christopher and Hurd conferred as the "contact group", made 
up of high-level officials of the United States, Russia, the 
European Union and the United Nations, its first meeting in 
London [as received] to coordinate efforts to bring peace to 
Bosnia. 
  NATO has given the Serbs until 0001 GMT on Wednesday [27 
April] to pull back all heavy weapons to at least 20 km from the 
U.N. safe haven of Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

