<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhu Rongji Meets Canadian Governor-General 26 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhu Rongji Meets Canadian Governor-General 26 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604123094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0919 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 26 (XINHUA) -- Acting Premier Zhu 
Rongji met with visiting Canadian Governor-General Ramon John 
Hnatyshyn at the Diaoyutai State Guesthouse here this afternoon. 
  Zhu welcomed Hnatyshyn and gave him greetings from Premier 
Li 
Peng -- away on a Central Asian official tour. 
  Hnatyshyn said that he was glad to meet Zhu again, whom he 
met with last may in Canada. 
  Zhu said that Hnatyshyn had very good talks with President 
Jiang Zemin yesterday, and that he believed that his current 
visit would further promote the friendly cooperative relations 
between China and Canada. 
  Touching on bilateral trade relations, Zhu said that China 
attaches great importance to its trade cooperation with canada, 
especially in the field of agriculture. 
  Zhu said that China was willing to further its trade 
relations with Canada, adding that the economies of the two 
countries are mutually complementary, and the potential for 
future cooperation was great. 
  The Chinese acting premier said that the economic recovery 
in 
canadian regions along the Pacific coast was better than that of 
the region along the atlantic coast. The reason was that the 
economic cooperation between canada's Pacific region and Asia 
had developed faster than that of the other regions in canada. 
  Hnatyshyn agreed with Zhu's views. He stressed that the most 
favored nations trading status between the two countries was 
unconditional, adding that developing cooperative relations 
between Canada and China was in the interests of both countries. 
  Sun Yongfu, chairman of the Chinese Government Reception 
Committee and vice-minister of railways, and Vice-Foreign 
Minister Jiang Enzhu, as well as Canadian senior officials 
accompanying the governor-general, took part in the meeting. 

</TEXT>

