<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Li Peng Visits Kazakhstan 26 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Li Peng Visits Kazakhstan 26 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Domestic Version of Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW2604132694 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1114 
GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2604132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondents Sun Zhanlin (1327 0594 2651) and Ju </F>
Mengjun (0215 1322 6511)] 
  [Text] Almaty, 26 Apr (XINHUA) -- Premier Li Peng and 
Kazakh President Nazarbayev held two rounds of talks at the 
presidential office here this morning. They had an in-depth 
exchange of views on Sino-Kazakh relations and issues of common 
interest. 
  The talks were conducted in a cordial and friendly 
atmosphere. Li Peng said: "Our talks have been fruitful. The 
talks, which have deepened mutual understanding and trust, will 
be conducive to further expanding relations between the two 
countries in various fields." 
  He added: China and Kazakhstan are neighbors sharing a long 
border. China attaches great importance to its friendship with 
Kazakhstan. The two countries hold identical or similar views 
on many international issues. He pointed out: Sino-Kazakh 
relations are new-type relations based on equality, mutual 
benefit, respect, and noninterference in each other's internal 
affairs. 
  Nazarbayev stated: Premier Li Peng's visit to Kazakhstan, 
the first in history by a Chinese leader, is a historic event in 
Kazakh-Chinese relations. He added: To develop relations with 
China is a priority of Kazakhstan's foreign policy. Kazakhstan 
will stick to the stance of noninterference in each other's 
internal affairs, will oppose national separatism and 
hegemonism, and will not allow "Eastern Turkistan" to carry out 
activities from Kazakhstan against China to the detriment of 
Kazakh-Chinese relations. Kazakhstan maintains that Taiwan is 
an integral part of the Chinese territory, and that Almaty will 
not have any official contacts whatsoever with Taiwan. 
  Li Peng expressed appreciation for Nazarbayev's stand that 
the Kazakh Government will not allow national separatists to 
engage in anti-Chinese activities from Kazakhstan. He also 
thanked the Kazakh Government for taking the correct stand on 
the Taiwan and Tibet issues. 
  The two leaders highly evaluated the Sino-Kazakh border 
agreement, which they believed is a historical event in 
bilateral relations and another important hallmark of the growth 
of Sino- Kazakh goodneighborly and friendly relations. The 
agreement will have a positive impact on expanding economic 
cooperation between the two countries. Li Peng said: The 
signing of the Sino-Kazakh border agreement once again shows to 
the entire world that Sino-Kazakh relations are founded on 
mutual trust and have strong vitality. He added: "We shall 
strive to build a new silk road together and will turn the 
Sino-Kazakh border into a boundary of peace, tranquility, 
friendship, and cooperation." 
  Discussing bilateral economic and trade relations, 
Nazarbayev 
noted there exists broad foundations for developing economic and 
trade relations based on equality and mutual benefit. He hoped 
to further enrich the contents of cooperation and expand the 
areas of cooperation at a level commensurate with the two 
countries' potential. Li Peng said: "Despite the large growth 
in bilateral trade in recent years, there is still room for 
further development. I entirely agree with Your Excellency the 
President's proposal for further developing cooperation between 
the two countries. China will adopt a positive approach toward 
this proposal." 
  LI Peng conveyed President Jiang Zemin's greetings to 
Nazarbayev, as well as the Chinese president's invitation to him 
to visit China once again. Nazarbayev asked Li Peng to relay 
his best wishes and gratitude to President Jiang Zemin. 

</TEXT>

