Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Li Peng Visits Kazakhstan 26 Apr </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Li Peng Visits Kazakhstan 26 Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Li Peng Comments on Investment </H4>

<F P=102> HK2704030294 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1503 GMT 
26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2704030294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Alma Ata, April 26 (CNS) -- At the end of his visit 
to four Central Asian countries, China's Premier Li Peng hosted 
a forum here with the delegation of Chinese entrepreneurs 
accompanying him on his visit, Mr. Li said that China would 
never seek its own sphere of influence in the region and would 
not hinder other countries from investing in the Central Asian 
countries. 
  Premier Li said that special attention would be given to the 
quality of commodities entering the Central Asian markets and 
legitimate business should be protected and speculation cracked 
down on. Border trade should continue to develop and its 
operational level enhanced. 
  In reply to a question on the issue of dual nationality put 
to him by a journalist today, the premier said that China did 
not recognize dual nationality as was made clear in China's Law 
on Nationality. There were now 50 million people in the world 
of Chinese origin living outside China with most of them living 
in Southeast Asian countries. The fact that such a large number 
of people of Chinese origin were living overseas was a 
historical result and China accepted this historical fact. 
China had offered them the right to choose their nationality. 
They could either choose Chinese nationality or that of the 
country in which they lived. That option meant that they could 
enjoy all the rights and fulfill the obligations of the country 
which they choose. 
  This morning, a Sino-Kazakh border agreement was signed here 
by Premier Li and the President of Kazakhstan, N. A. Nazarbayev. 
  The Sino-Kazakh border is over 1,700 kilometres in length 
and 
the two sides reached agreement on more than 1,600 kilometres of 
its length. At their meeting, the Kazakh president said that 
Kazakhstan adhered to the principle of non-interference in the 
internal affairs of other countries and opposed national 
splittism and hegemonism. Kazakhstan, he said, would not allow 
"East Turkistan" to stage anti-China activities and undermine 
Kazakh-Chinese relations in Kazakh territory. 
  President Nazarbayev also said that Kazakhstan considered 
Taiwan an inalienable part of the People's Republic of China and 
Kazakhstan would not have any official contacts with Taiwan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4014 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi082_c_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-082 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Comments on Li Peng's Central Asia Visits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Comments on Li Peng's Central Asia Visits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704081494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0744 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704081494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Almaty, April 27 (XINHUA) -- Premier Li Peng's visit 
to Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Kyrgyzstan and Kazakhstan marks the 
beginning of a new era in China's relationship with Central 
Asian nations. 
  Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Dai Bingguo, who has been 
traveling with the premier, made the remark in an interview here 
today, the last day of Li's 10-day tour of Central Asia. 
  Li's trip is a complete success with fruitful results that 
will generate far-reaching impact, said Dai. 
  In their talks, Premier Li had reached full agreement with 
leaders of the four countries on ways of furthering bilateral 
ties, and on regional and international issues of common 
concern, according to Dai. 
  "The visit has achieved the desired objective of enhancing 
mutual understanding, promoting friendship and expanding 
mutually- beneficial cooperation," he said. 
  Dai said the principles Li stated during the tour on 
developing political as well as economic relations with the 
Central Asian nations are "a long-term policy." 
  As time goes by, these principles will show its increasing 
vitalities, Dai said, calling the prospect "inspiring" for 
cooperation with Central Asia in both political and economic 
fields. 
  Referring to the signing of the Sino-Kazakh border agreement 
and the common wish expressed by China and Kyrgyzstan to solve 
the border issue at an early date, Dai said Li's tour served to 
further improve China's "environment in the neighborhood." 
  "We hope to see an early successful settlement of the border 
issue with all the neighboring countries to the north, and turn 
our common boundary into a bond of lasting peace and 
friendship," he said. 
  After the tour of the four former Soviet republics, Li will 
continue his trip to Mongolia for a two-day official visit that 
will end on April 29. 

</TEXT>

