<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decision Delays Cabinet Formation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Decision Delays Cabinet Formation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604055894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0515 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604055894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 (XINHUA) -- The decision by the 
Social Democratic Party (SDP) to quit the ruling coalition has 
caused an impasse in the formation of a new Japanese cabinet 
headed by newly elected Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata. 
  The SDP's decision is an angry reaction to the abrupt 
establishment of a parliamentary group that excludes the 
socialists. 
  In a statement issued after a meeting early today, SDP 
Chairman Toriichi Murayamua said that the formation of such a 
group infringed upon the relationship of trust among the 
coalition parties. 
  The 130-member parliamentary alliance named "Kaishin" 
(Renovation) includes the Shinseito Party, the Japan New Party, 
the Democratic Socialist Party, the Jiyuto (Liberals) and 
Kaikaku No Kai. 
  This new group will be the largest force in the coalition 
and 
will have more members than the SDP. 
  Hata earlier today invited the SDP to remain in the 
coalition, while defending the formation of the parliamentary 
group. 
  "Unless we have such a group, coalition parties will not be 
able to cope with the difficult problems and act in solidarity," 
Hata said. 
  Several meetings were being held this morning to discuss the 
situation after the SDP announced it was quitting the coalition. 
  Hata's policy speech to the Diet scheduled for Tuesday 
afternoon has been postponed because of the delay in forming a 
new government. 
  A large-scale reshuffling of the cabinet now seems 
unavoidable since the SDP held six cabinet posts in former Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's coalition cabinet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4030 </DOCNO>
