<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Calls For Talks With SDP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Calls For Talks With SDP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604134894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1032 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 (XINHUA) -- Japan's newly elected 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata today called for talks with the 
breakaway Social Democratic Party (SDP) in a bid to draw it back 
to the ruling coalition fold. 
  Hata, while appealing to SDP to remain within the coalition, 
warned that he will form a new cabinet even without the SDP, the 
biggest party in the alliance. 
  He had this to say, "we cannot spend so much time" on this 
matter. 
  SDP quit the coalition earlier today, in a move that 
deprived 
the coalition of its parliamentary majority, leaving the new 
prime minister crippled at the start of his administration and 
the country facing the prospect of possible early elections. 
  The SDP decision of pullout was approved formally at an 
emergency meeting of the party's central executive committee. 
  At the meeting SDP Chairman Tomiichi Murayama attacked the 
sudden formation last night of a new parliamentary bloc grouping 
the coalition's centrist and conservative parties but excluding 
the SDP, saying it destroyed the coalition structure. 
  The SDP holds 74 seats in the 511-member lower house. Beside 
the 130 lawmakers already committed to the new bloc, the 
centrist Komeito (Clean Government Party) is reportedly ready to 
bring in its 52 members as well. 
  Against this, the opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) 
holds 206 seats. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4031 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi082_d_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-082 </AU>
