<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Sworn In as Premier </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Sworn In as Premier </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804035794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0329 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804035794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Newly-elected Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata was sworn in by Emperor Akihito today, 
formally taking over as Japan's 51st prime minister. 
  Hata, elected by parliament on Monday, has failed to reach 
agreement among coalition party leaders on a new cabinet and 
appeared set to form the first minority administration in four 
decades. 
  Hata will make a last-ditch effort later in the day to 
persuade the socialists to return to the ruling coalition. 
  The Social Democratic Party (the socialists), the biggest 
partner in the eight-month-old coalition, walked out on Tuesday 
[26 April] in an angry reaction to the establishment of a rival 
parliamentary bloc grouping five coalition parties but excluding 
the socialists within just hours of Hata's election. 
  The socialists' move wold deprive Hata of his parliamentary 
majority and raise prospects of a period of weak minority rule 
followed by forced early elections. 
  Hata took over from Morihiro Hosokawa, who resigned abruptly 
on April 8 after just eight months in office over his dubious 
personal finances and a Diet (parliament) stalemate. 

</TEXT>

