<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Notes Formation of Minority Cabinet in Japan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Notes Formation of Minority Cabinet in Japan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804090594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0744 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804090594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Japan's new Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata launched his cabinet today to rule with a 
minority coalition government, the first of its kind in nearly 
four decades. 
  The inauguration of the Hata administration came after 
Social 
Democratic Party (SDP) Chairman Tomiichi Murayama rejected 
Hata's last-minute call for SDP to return to the nine-month-old 
coalition. 
  The largest political force in the alliance led by former 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, SDP on Tuesday announced its 
withdrawal from the ruling bloc to protest the formation of a 
130-strong parliamentary group called Kaishin (Renovation) that 
excludes the Social Democrats. 
  The Hata coalition now has only 182 seats in the decisive 
511- member House of Representatives, far short of a majority 
of 256. 
  Earlier today, Emperor Akihito appointed Hata, leader of the 
coalition's key party Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party), as 
Japan's 51st premier in a morning ceremony at the Imperial 
Palace. 
  The appointment had been delayed by the political unrest 
sparked by Kaishin's establishment on Monday and the subsequent 
SDP defection from the coalition. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

