<F P=100> Sub-Saharan Africa </F>
<H3> <TI>   South Africa's First Non-Racial Election Begins </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    South Africa's First Non-Racial Election Begins </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604055694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0522 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604055694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg, April 26 (XINHUA) -- The first 
non-racial election in South Africa began today, ending 350 
years of the apartheid rule in the country. 
  The historic elections are recognized by the international 
community as a momentous event and the completion of the 
transition from apartheid to democracy. The elections are the 
final repudiation of institutionalized racism in the world. 
  About 22.71 million South African voters will elect a 
400-seat national assembly and provincial legislatures during 
the three days of elections. 
  An estimated 16.2 million members of the Black community, or 
72 percent of the total number of voters in South Africa, will 
be voting for the first time in their life, marking the end of 
342 years of the White domination. 
  Twenty-seven parties, including the African National 
Congress 
(ANC), the National Party and the Inkatha Freedom Party, are 
contesting the elections, with another eight at regional level. 
  Today is the first day of the elections, or special voting 
day. Voters who are physically disabled, pregnant, infirm, aged, 
and ill, and members of the defense force, police force and 
national peace-keeping force, are voting today at about 800 
special polling stations, both fixed and mobile, across the 
country. 
  Hospitals, homes and care centers catering for more than 200 
patients are fixed voting stations while those with less than 
200 patients are being visited by a mobile station which will 
remain at the institution until all those who wish to vote have 
voted. 
  Most of the South African voters will cast their ballots on 
Wednesday and Thursday. 
  On Wednesday and Thursday, 9,000 polling stations throughout 
the country will be opened at 07:00 (0500 GMT) on Friday at 
between 800 and 1,000 counting centers around the country. 
  Initial election results are expected to be released 48 
hours 
after the elections and final results may be announced by the 
independent electoral commission on May 1 or May 2. 
  The ANC, which enjoys high reputation for its anti-apartheid 
struggle during the past decades, is likely to win a sweeping 
victory in the elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

